    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2001_Solutions_2001s_page_002_1",
    "text": "We cannot have a = 1, since 1 - 2\" # 2001 for any n. Thus the only possibility is a = 13. One easily checks that a = 13,n = 2 is a solution; all that remains is to check that no other n works. In fact, if n > 2, then 13\"+1 = 2001 = 1 (mod 8). But 13\"+1 = 13 (mod 8) since n is even, contradiction. Thus a = 13, n = 2 is the unique solution.",
